TY  - JOUR
AU  - Acemoglu, Daron
AU  - Tahbaz-Salehi, Alireza
T1  - The Macroeconomics of Supply Chain Disruptions 
PY  - 2025
Y1  - 2025/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdae038
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 92
IS  - 2
SP  - 656
EP  - 695
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper develops a model to study the macroeconomic implications of supply chain disruptions with three key ingredients: (i) a firm-level network of customized supplier–customer links that generate relationship-specific productivity gains; (ii) bargaining over these relationship-specific surpluses; and (iii) an extensive margin of adjustment, whereby firms decide to form or sever relations with suppliers and customers. We establish equilibrium existence and uniqueness, provide characterization results, and present a number of comparative statics that show how supply chains and aggregate output respond to shocks. We also show that equilibrium supply chains are inefficient and exhibit an inherent fragility: small shocks can lead to discontinuous changes in output, even though the efficient allocation is always continuous in the same shocks. We explore several macroeconomic implications of this fragility.
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdae038
ER  - 




